answers.body_markdown:
[Error boundaries][1] are designed to catch errors during rendering, in lifecycle methods, and in constructors of the whole tree below them. 

If you want to catch unhandled promise errors globally (instead of handling it directly in component), you can use [window.onunhandledrejection][3].

    window.onunhandledrejection = function(e) {
      console.log(e.reason);
    }

but it&#39;s not supported in all browsers by default.

Little hacky solution would be to call `this.setState(() =&gt; { throw err; });` in  `catch` of your promise.


  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/error-boundaries.html
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/PromiseRejectionEvent

